So if `scale_h` is true, then `sidx` advances only when `(y & 1) == 1` (odd rows). That means for even rows, the same source row is used again. That is correct for vertical downscaling: each source row is used for two output rows (since `scale_h` means half height). But in the original, the copy for `!scale_v` is done for every row, but the source pointer only advances on odd rows. So the even rows copy the same source as the previous row.

Now, the optimized version for `!gdv->scale_v`:
```
